Honestly right now I am too exhausted to try and start the process again somehow. Maybe I will again one day. But not now. I'm burned out.

The idea that the mere passage of time bars me from a correct diagnosis is frustrating and, quite frankly, saddening. I am certain I have not failed, but the diagnostic criteria has failed me. Yet the concern I am "not autistic enough" was realised on Saturday.

I read that the "atypical autism" diagnosis was given to children deemed "too young" to be diagnosed with ASD. With the change in diagnostic criteria in 2013, these children were susbequently diagnosed with ASD. I wasn't. I'm an adult. The criteria just said "no, you're fine".

I show a great deal of emotion and empathy, I don't display the kind of rigidity they look for. That's what pushed me to 'borderline' despite having struggled all my life. The diagnostic criteria still leans in the direction of diagnosing boys/men.

When I say "people like me", I mean people who have been masking for 30-odd years and have turned it into a fine at great cost to themselves. Who don't match the very limited assumptions about autism that the medical profession insists on clinging to.

I've had time to think about this and I've decided that I'm describing this as "Old World" autism. "Before Age of Sigmar" autism.

This is me trying to reconcile the fact the current diagnostic criteria pushes people like me out of receiving a proper diagnosis. https://t.co/bdeaMjaAwy

13) Beautiful Desolation. I don't see enough chant about this game and it's so frustrating! Went in not knowing what to expect and came out with it being one of my favourite games ever. Soundtrack slaps. Another one I look forward to diving into again.
12) The Dark Side of the Moon. Was really hyped for this one and it didn't disappoint. Great twisty storyline and the dev team are lovely.
11) The Shapeshifting Detective. A really fun concept of detective work and mystery solving.
10) The Infectious Madness of Doctor Dekker. This one was very good at jumpscares and making my jaw drop. And making me realise I can't read people.
9) Dark Nights with Poe and Monroe. Another FMV gem! Lots of fun and made me smile.
8) Contradiction. My introduction to the joy of FMV games. So good I played it through twice.
7) Red Dead Redemption 2. Speaking of crying. Lots of crying. Absolutely stunning game and I barely scratched the surface. Can't wait to dive in again.
6) Yakuza 6. This felt like the 'goodbye to an era' one. It was good but I was getting a bit of series fatigue honestly. Cried a lot at the end.
5) Yakuza 5. This one was a real trip. More multiple storylines weaving together. Very emotional rollercoaster.
4) Yakuza 4. AKIYAMA! That is all. Actually no, not all. Multiple character stories weaving together was heaps of fun.
3) Yakuza 3. Very different feel, combat was a bit more tricky. Loved the Okinawa setting, big dose of sunshine. Rikiya is best boy.
2) Yakuza Kiwami 2. I wouldn't say this was "better" than Kiwami and 0, they're all on the same level. Loved the hostess club sidequest.

1) Yakuza Kiwami. This one was such a delight, seeing the original that started it all in Yakuza 0 graphics was sublime. Really took more time over sidequests as they were so much fun, especially Majima Everywhere
Games I completed this year in no particular order, let's gooo

tl;dr: Media, stop treating this like some kind of revelation. It's bad and that should be obvious.

I've been conditioned to think 'loud = violence'. And that is messed up. I would also be punished for innocuous things, which means I still feel a fleeting terror every time I do something like knock something over or spill something.

As a result of repeated physical punishment as a child, as an adult I am scared of sudden loud noises and anyone raising their voice to me. Why? Because yelling would almost certainly be followed by violence when I was a child.

I'm certain this debate attracts the 'rahrahrah well I was smacked as a kid and it never did ME any harm' crew and good for you but also shut up please, just because you don't perceive it as doing you any harm doesn't mean it didn't do anyone any harm ever.

I swear I see the headline 'smacking children isn't a good thing, actually' come up in the media every few years or so, like it's brand new information. Anyone who was subjected to that as a child could easily tell you that for a lot less funding.

Uff, sorry, I was due to go into one rage this pride month and that was probably it

I will add that yes, being neurodivergent can influence how one perceives and goes about intimate/romantic relationships. It definitely influences how I perceive them. But my sexuality is not a tick box on a doctor's list.

That shit stays with you. And to then go into adult society where you are made to feel like the exception to the norm? It doesn't feel great honestly. And to see people blindly posting stupid, uninformed shit like that spectrum just reinforces that.

Sex and relationships are SO ingrained into society's psyche that it makes anyone who doesn't want all that, or doesn't want it in the way most people do, feel isolated. I spent a lot of my formative years being told I was 'frigid', 'stuck-up' and a 'prude'.

The whole 'portraying asexuality as down one end of a scale that has 'normal' in the middle' is the kind of shit medical professionals try to pull. It says we're missing something, unwell, not normal, and need to be "fixed".
He told me wanting/desiring sex and relationships was a 'normal human thing', and the fact I did not desire either supported a diagnosis. I felt like my sexuality was being pathologized.

That spectrum thing going around has made me really angry so I'm going to share something.

A medical professional tried to use the fact I was asexual to support his theory that I had ASD. There was already ample evidence for that, me being asexual does not come into it.
That shit plays into the whole 'oh you're just xyz' type response when we tell people we're ace and I'm sick of it

Honestly? Funniest bit out of the lot of this so far is Sawako being Goromi's bodyguard.
- Nakagawa's office is in the building next door to the Sotenbori Sky Finance office
- Sawako does a lot of the managing of The Cabaret Grand behind the scenes. If she fucks up on something, she's made to dress up and manage the floor. Customer service is a real mean punishment

- The outfit she wore for that test has become one of her disguises. If she needs to speak to Nishitani, she usually has to go to The Cabaret Grand dressed as a hostess
- The Cabaret Grand is under Kijin Clan ownership, much to Sengoku's chagrin

- Nakagawa went to Sky Finance to get the loan she needed to set up her office. Her test was to work as a hostess at Club Elise for a week. She was very harshly rejected from Club Mars when she was younger because she didn't fit the bill, so this was a heck of a test for her

- Sawako is expected to drive ~6 hours each way to Kamurocho to pick Goromi up because she refuses to use the shinkansen
- Goromi really likes to put Sawako through the ringer
- No, Sawako doesn't get to ditch this position on becoming Captain

- Goromi is officially Nishitani's girlfriend and the rank and file are expected to respect and treat her as such.
- Sawako is forced-- I mean appointed as her bodyguard
- Majima is Nishitani's boyfriend too (get you someone who can do many)

Worldbuilding includes!
- Sengoku as a really fun antagonist
- A cryptid who may or may not be Nishitani
- Said cryptid is the focus of an ongoing investigation by Nakagawa
- Nakagawa probably does some investigative work for the Kijin Clan instead of paying protection money
Not to gush or anything but like I'm really enjoying the worldbuilding I've done around my Yakuza OCs?? It's a bit silly and out of step with the original timeline but that's okay!

I'm not holding out much hope for my autism assessment happening any time soon either. Things are being done, and honestly, they're only being done because an autism assessment was recommended by my ADHD psychiatrist. Without that it'd be like pissing in the wind.

I was extremely fortunate that I was able to get my diagnosis privately. But it shouldn't be like that. It shouldn't be down to luck or how fortunate you are. It should be available to everyone when they need it.
I had a snowball's chance in hell of getting an ADHD assessment on the NHS. I would either not get one before I turned 40, or the service would just cease to exist before anything came of it.
